{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"96e267a2-eb1c-4a29-8ac7-242500ece092","content":"The change is straightforward. In your project file, simply **remove** (or set to `false`) the `<UseVSTest>` property:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Before -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n\n<!-- After -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Why this is enough:** MSTest.Sdk 3.8.0 uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform **by default**. The `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` property was explicitly opting you back into the legacy VSTest runner. Removing it (or setting it to `false`) gives you the default behavior — Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\n**Things to be aware of after switching:**\n\n1. **CLI changes** — Use `dotnet test` as before, but some VSTest-specific command-line options (e.g., `--logger`, `--filter` syntax) may differ slightly.\n2. **`.runsettings`** — Most settings carry over, but review any VSTest-specific adapter settings.\n3. **CI pipelines** — If your CI uses `dotnet test --logger trx`, verify the TRX output still works as expected (it should, but confirm).\n4. **Extensions** — If you relied on VSTest adapters/extensions, check that Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalents are available.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"451891ef-f6f2-4e84-9041-ab01ed71d4f9","outputTokens":355,"requestId":"982C:7D115:1710A5:1E5E00:69FFD85D"},"id":"edfd4f49-2349-45e9-9967-2fe987914590","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:59:20.069Z","parentId":"68e21e29-9c10-45bb-b654-076b2515c6c3"}
